</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
214 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEBATE OVER CAPITAL GAINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Democrats have lost the last two presidential elections because they have 
lost touch with those whose votes they need to win an election (the 
middle-class American.) 
</P>
<P>
The Democrats presently are against a proposed reduction in the capital gains 
tax as it will only benefit the rich and the upper class. Why don't the 
Democrats propose a reduction in the capital gains tax that will benefit most 
Americans in one way or another? Why not treat interest income as capital gains 
and then the reduction in the capital gains tax will affect every American who 
has money in a bank account, etc? 
</P>
<P>
I see no reason why a person, rich or poor, should be penalized for saving 
money and have to pay a high rate of tax on the low rate of interest earned on 
the money. One reason that Americans do not save money is they earn 6% to 9% 
interest and after taxes their return is from 4% to 6%. When Americans do not 
save money, we then have to keep our interest rates high so that foreigners 
will deposit money in our financial institutions and purchase T-bills, etc. 
Therefore, if we can encourage saving by lowering the tax rate on interest 
income (by considering it a capital gain) we may also very well lower the 
interest rate we have to pay to borrow money. 
</P>
<P>
ORRIN H. TURBOW 
</P>
<P>
Chatsworth 
</P>
</TEXT>
