<HEADLINE>
<P>
VOTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is not only an honor but a sacred trust to have the power to make daily 
decisions that affect the lives of every American. Each time we go to the polls 
we vote for our chosen representatives as "our voice" in our government, and so 
endow those individuals with the awesome authority to speak for us. But since 
we don't receive daily memos from them as to what's transpiring in the meeting 
rooms of our nation's Capitol, nor do we have box seats at Senate debates, we 
rarely know what legislation has been proposed, enacted or repealed until it is 
a fait accompli. So, it is with a deep sense of shock and outrage to hear of a 
proposed bill (S-874), which calls for "instant voter registration" -- a plan 
to automatically register people to vote when they renew their driver's 
license. 
</P>
<P>
According to the sponsor of this "motor-voter" bill, Sen. Wendell Ford (D-Ky.), 
"It will remove obstacles from voter registration and encourage more people to 
vote." 
</P>
<P>
Surely at a time when fake IDs are as easily purchased as a box of Cracker Jack 
by illegal aliens and others who have ulterior motives for possessing them, the 
intelligence and motives of the sponsor and endorsers of this legislation must 
be seriously questioned. 
</P>
<P>
To allow such irresponsible and dangerous legislation to go unchallenged is to 
open the door to "voting by phone" or even total abolishment of the need to 
register. 
</P>
<P>
RUTH COFFEY 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
