<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLITICAL LABELS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Philip Dunne's excellent column "Pinning Down Political Labels" (Editorial 
Page, July 29) pointed out the semantic absurdities going about these days. 
Preposterous people, such as James Watt, are being described by equally 
preposterous -- and tortured -- phrases, "radical conservative," for one. 
</P>
<P>
A solution to this, it seems to me, would be the revival of a word which seems 
to have vanished, without a trace, from the American political vocabulary, 
namely: reactionary. It is not an epithet. It is a simple, direct, description 
of a political viewpoint. Its return to our language would spare us the 
absurdities and euphemisms which now irritate us. 
</P>
<P>
Calling James Watt, Jesse Helms, and others too numerous to mention, 
"conservatives" (no matter how you qualify the word) is about as accurate as 
calling Hitler a troublemaker. 
</P>
<P>
ELLIOTT REID 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
