<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: STAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When "Oh! Calcutta!" cast members put on their clothes and went home after 
Sunday night's performance in New York, it marked the close of what has been 
billed as "the world's longest-running erotic stage musical." The show, born of 
the 1960s era of "free love," ended with its 5,959th performance. The revue 
opened Off-Broadway on June 17, 1969 and has moved to several New York theaters 
since then. There were 10 in the cast then. The final performance had eight in 
the opening number, "Taking Off the Robe," and 11 in the finale as a few alumni 
returned for a final scamper in white robes and birthday suits. With the 
5,832th Broadway performance of "A Chorus Line" this weekend -- it opened a few 
months earlier but has had a less-intensive schedule -- "Oh! Calcutta!'s" mark 
is expected to fall this fall. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
