<HEADLINE>
<P>
EARNINGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Microsemi Corp., a Santa Ana semiconductor manufacturer, reported a loss of 
$707,000 for its fiscal third quarter ended July 2, its first quarterly loss in 
eight years. The loss contrasts with earnings of $548,000 for the corresponding 
quarter the year before. The firm put the primary blame for the loss on the 
cancellation of a $10-million contract with a San Diego-based unit of General 
Instrument Corp. Microsemi had expected the contract to contribute $1.2 million 
in sales and $400,000 in gross profit for the latest quarter. David R. Sonksen, 
a Microsemi vice president, said the company has filed a lawsuit against 
General Instrument, claiming that the New York-based electronics firm breached 
the terms of its contract with Microsemi. Microsemi's revenues grew 21% to 
$26.4 million for the quarter, up from $21.7 million for the period in the 
previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
